## Sequence Visualization

* **GeneRunner** – Sequence viewer/editor. Can translate DNA → protein (be sure to pick the correct reading frame). *Windows-only; installers often hosted on software repositories.*

  * Download / info: Gene Runner (Softpedia). ([Softpedia][https://www.softpedia.com/get/Science-CAD/Gene-Runner.shtml])

* **Jalview** – Alignment viewer and editor that highlights amino-acid conservation and many annotation/colour schemes. Best used *after* you generate alignments with a dedicated aligner.

  * Website & docs: [https://www.jalview.org/](https://www.jalview.org/) (manual & downloads). ([jalview.org][https://www.jalview.org/help.html])

---

## Sequence Alignment

* **MAFFT** – Multiple-sequence aligner with several algorithms (choose method based on dataset size and accuracy needs). Use MAFFT for both nucleotide and protein alignments; consult docs for method selection (e.g., L-INS-i, FFT-NS-2).

  * Website & download: [https://mafft.cbrc.jp/alignment/software/](https://mafft.cbrc.jp/alignment/software/) . ([mafft.cbrc.jp][https://mafft.cbrc.jp/alignment/software/])

* **trimAl** (trimming) – Automated trimming of poorly aligned or gappy regions before downstream phylogeny building; recommended as a step after alignment.

  * Docs / download: [https://trimal.cgenomics.org/](https://trimal.cgenomics.org/) or [https://trimal.readthedocs.io/](https://trimal.readthedocs.io/) . ([trimal.cgenomics.org][https://trimal.cgenomics.org/])

* **BLAST (NCBI)** – Standard suite for sequence similarity searches. Choose the algorithm that matches your query and database:

  * `blastn` — nucleotide → nucleotide
  * `blastp` — protein → protein
  * `tblastn` — protein → translated nucleotide database
  * `blastx` — translated nucleotide (as protein) → protein database
  * Web and standalone executables available (use command-line BLAST for batch jobs).
  * BLAST interface & docs: [https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Blast.cgi](https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Blast.cgi) . ([blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov][https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Blast.cgi])

---

## Phylogenetics & Visualization

* **iTOL (Interactive Tree Of Life)** – Web-based tree visualization/annotation tool with rich export and annotation options — great for polishing figures for presentations or papers.

  * Website / docs: [https://itol.embl.de/](https://itol.embl.de/) . ([itol.embl.de][https://itol.embl.de/])

* **MEGA X** – Desktop software for constructing phylogenies (multiple inference methods), model testing, and basic sequence analyses. GUI + command-line options available for various OSes.

  * Website & downloads: [https://www.megasoftware.net/](https://www.megasoftware.net/) . ([megasoftware.net][https://www.megasoftware.net/])

---

## Quick tips

* **Trim before tree-building.** Trim low-quality or ambiguously aligned regions (trimAl) to avoid artefacts in phylogenies. ([trimal.cgenomics.org][https://trimal.cgenomics.org/])
* **Pick the right BLAST algorithm.** Understand whether your input and target DB are nucleotide or protein (BLASTn/blastp/tblastn/blastx). ([blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov][https://blast.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/Blast.cgi])
* **Align before visualizing.** Tools like Jalview expect an alignment input to show conservation; use MAFFT (or other aligners) first. ([mafft.cbrc.jp][https://mafft.cbrc.jp/alignment/software/])


